div.note:
1124 Apollinaris argued that if Christ were perfect God and perfect man, there would be two Christs, the Son
of God by nature and the Son of God by adoption. Hence He taught that Christ was partly God and partly man;
that He received from the Virgin His body and the lower, irrational soul which is the condition of bodily life;
while His rational Spirit was Divine. On this theory the ‘whole man,’ as Hilary says, was not born of the Virgin.
Hilary denies the threefold division. The soul in every case, Christ’s included, is, he says, the immediate work
of God.
